# Avoid Duplication

Before creating anything new (a function, file, type, helper, or dependency),
FIRST check whether it already exists.

- Search the codebase for an existing function/type/util that does the same or a
  similar job; reuse or extend it instead of writing a new one.
- Before adding a dependency, check whether an already-installed one covers the need.
- If you find two things doing the same job, flag the redundancy and propose
  consolidating into one canonical implementation.
- Don't fork near-identical logic - one source per concern.

(Complements `code-structure`'s DRY/rule-of-three, which covers *when to extract*
generics; this rule is about *checking first* to avoid creating duplicates.)
